Lectotype male of 
<taxonomicName box="[511,640,1824,1848]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Platycerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="352" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pacificus">
<emphasis box="[511,640,1824,1848]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="352">P. pacificus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(USNM), 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[762,948,1823,1848]" pageId="6" pageNumber="352">here designated</emphasis>
, labeled: a) handwritten “ 
<taxonomicName box="[1243,1344,1824,1848]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Platycerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="352" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pacificus">
<emphasis box="[1243,1344,1824,1848]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="352">pacificus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
/ Csy.”; b) “CASEY / bequest / 1925”; c) on orange paper, “TYPE USNM / [36210]”; d) “ 
<taxonomicName box="[1070,1331,1859,1883]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Platyceroides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="352" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pacificus">
<emphasis box="[1070,1331,1859,1883]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="352">Platyceroides pacificus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
/ (
<bibRefCitation author="Casey" pageId="6" pageNumber="352" refString="Casey, T. L. (1889) Coleopterological notices. I. Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences, 5, 39 - 96. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1749 - 6632.1890. tb 57003. x" type="journal article" year="1889">Casey, 1889</bibRefCitation>
) / det. M.J. Paulsen 2016”; e) on red paper, “ 
<taxonomicName box="[714,834,1895,1919]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Platycerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="352" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[714,834,1895,1919]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="352">Platycerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
/ 
<taxonomicName authority="Casey" authorityName="Casey" box="[856,1033,1896,1920]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Platyceroides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="352" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pacificus">
<emphasis box="[856,957,1896,1920]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="352">pacificus</emphasis>
Casey
</taxonomicName>
/ Lectotype / det. MJ Paulsen”.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1823,2028]" pageId="6" pageNumber="352">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,330,1931,1956]" pageId="6" pageNumber="352">Taxonomy.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Casey" box="[344,502,1932,1956]" pageId="6" pageNumber="352" refString="Casey, T. L. (1889) Coleopterological notices. I. Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences, 5, 39 - 96. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1749 - 6632.1890. tb 57003. x" type="journal article" year="1889">Casey (1889)</bibRefCitation>
reported examining three specimens, but only one is present in the USNM collection, and I designate it as the lectotype. It has male genitalia that are barely discernible from those of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Platyceroides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="352" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="agassii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="352">P. agassii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, it has a much larger antennal club, is darker in coloration and has more robust metatibiae (
<figureCitation box="[1391,1437,2003,2028]" captionStart="FIGURE 3 – 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1558,1580]" captionTargetBox="[175,1428,241,1507]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,195,1536]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3 – 4. Platyceroides agassii species group, males. Platyceroides agassii: 3 A, dorsal habitus; 3 B, male genitalia. Platyceroides pacificus: 4 A, dorsal habitus; 4 B, flagellum of male genitalia." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/582453/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="352">Fig.</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,680]" pageId="7" pageNumber="353">
<materialsCitation ID-GBIF-Occurrence="1503414412" county="Eel River" elevation="2000" location="In" municipality="However" pageId="7" pageNumber="353" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="California" typeStatus="holotype">
4A). Additional specimens matching the 
<typeStatus box="[629,727,151,176]" pageId="7" pageNumber="353">holotype</typeStatus>
appear to be allopatric with 
<taxonomicName box="[1068,1179,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Platyceroides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="353" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="agassii">
<emphasis box="[1068,1179,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="353">P. agassii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and are distributed at much higher elevations (most specimens examined are from ~ 
<quantity box="[852,937,188,212]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="353" unit="m" value="2000.0">
<elevation box="[852,937,188,212]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="353" unit="m" value="2000.0">2000 m</elevation>
</quantity>
) and farther inland, north of the 
<collectingCounty box="[1301,1408,188,213]" pageId="7" pageNumber="353">Eel River</collectingCounty>
in 
<collectingRegion box="[151,265,223,248]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="7" pageNumber="353">California</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation box="[280,365,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURES 25 – 26" captionStartId="28.[151,264,1873,1895]" captionTargetBox="[161,1428,416,1839]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[151,1436,401,1852]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURES 25 – 26. Distribution of Platyceroides species. 25, Platyceroides agassii species group: P. agassii (blue squares); P. pacificus (orange circles). 26, P. pampinatus group: P. infernus (blue squares); P. pampinatus (orange circles)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/582463/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="353">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
). I considered treating 
<taxonomicName box="[624,753,224,248]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Platyceroides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="353" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pacificus">
<emphasis box="[624,753,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="353">P. pacificus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName box="[940,1047,224,248]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Platyceroides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="353" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="agassii">
<emphasis box="[940,1047,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="353">P. agassii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, because there is far less variation between the male genitalia of the two taxa than is usually present between 
<taxonomicName box="[1005,1158,260,284]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Platyceroides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="353" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1005,1158,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="353">Platyceroides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species. 
<collectingMunicipality box="[1263,1367,261,284]" pageId="7" pageNumber="353">However</collectingMunicipality>
, there are slight differences in the simple flagellum, with the enlarged portion of the apex smaller and with a shorter median process (
<figureCitation box="[354,429,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 3 – 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1558,1580]" captionTargetBox="[175,1428,241,1507]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,195,1536]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3 – 4. Platyceroides agassii species group, males. Platyceroides agassii: 3 A, dorsal habitus; 3 B, male genitalia. Platyceroides pacificus: 4 A, dorsal habitus; 4 B, flagellum of male genitalia." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/582453/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="353">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
B). 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:0382520FFFD1FFBCFF53F2A68436FD76:8EF4B5C2FFD0FFBCFE19F57E87BCFEBA" box="[477,500,333,356]" county="Eel River" municipality="However" name="In" pageId="7" pageNumber="353" stateProvince="California">In</location>
combination with the allopatry, distinctly larger antennal club, and other the morphological differences it seems more straightforward to treat the taxon as distinct.
</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
