<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="353" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,680]" pageId="7" pageNumber="353">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,511,536]" pageId="7" pageNumber="353">Remarks.</emphasis>
Specimens of 
<taxonomicName box="[489,620,512,536]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Platyceroides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="353" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pacificus">
<emphasis box="[489,620,512,536]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="353">P. pacificus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
typically have elytra with a shiny appearance but vary from glossy to weakly micropunctate under high magnification. However, the two 
<taxonomicName box="[954,1088,548,572]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Platyceroides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="353" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pacificus">
<emphasis box="[954,1088,548,572]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="353">P. pacificus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens seen from Trinity County, 
<collectingRegion box="[254,371,583,608]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="7" pageNumber="353">California</collectingRegion>
, have distinct microsculpture and appear slightly opaque. Among coastal species such sculpturing is otherwise confined to the 
<taxonomicName box="[614,775,621,644]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Platyceroides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="353" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pampinatus">
<emphasis box="[614,775,621,644]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="353">P. pampinatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group. Because of this, genitalic dissection is the best method of verifying and identification.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
